    b.
        Every eight bits, or at an other predefined interval, the data sent down the wire is summed modulo 2. This data includes a parity bit. If the result of this sum is 0 (so the sum of the data is even), then an error has occurred. This is because the parity bit is chosen in light of the rest of the data such that the result of this sum is 1 (so the sum is odd). If the result of the sum is not odd, then an error has occurred either in the transmission of the data or in the computation of the initial parity bit value or in the computation of the final sum of the data.
    c.
        Echo Check
5.
    a?
        A sample of the sound is taken at some specified frequency, known as the sample rate. This means that every 1/frequency, a sample of the sound (voltage/amperage from the microphone etc) is taken and stored in a file. This is an analogue value, however, so it is condensed into a certain amount of bits, known as the sample resolution. This allows for a file of size sample resolution * frequency * length of sound to be stored; the file contains frequency * length of sound samples or numbers represented in binary which represent the state of the microphone at the time 1/frequency after the previous sample, or the start of the recording.
    b.
        1.
            Increasing the sample rate
        2.
            Increasing the sample resolution
    c.
        Because in lossy compression data is permanently and irrevocably removed, which will reduce the quality of the sound file. The musician likely wants to preserve the quality of the sound file for the purposes of redistribution or just because most people would like a full quality copy.
    d?
        ASCII uses only seven bits and encodes primarily english characters. Unicode can encode much more characters including from non-western langauges, emojis etc
        Unicode uses more bits. UTF-8 uses eight bits per ASCII (and some latin) character(s), and otherwise may use more bits via the use of control characters in order to be able to represent characters
